Napoli, Campania, Italy":"Napoli, Campania, Italië","Napoli, Campania, Italie":"Napoli, Napoli, Campania, Italië"},"en":{"about 1290–1341":"about 1290–1341","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1294–1361":"1294–1361","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1275–1308":"1275–1308","about 1290":"about 1290","10 May 1327":"10 May 1327","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1250":"1250","1393":"1393","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1377":"1377","about 1288":"about 1288","1308":"1308","bet 1322 and 1325":"1323","Bassily, Hainaut, Belgium":"Bassilly, Hainaut, Belgium","Italy":"Italy","Napoli, Campania, Italy":"Naples, Campania, Italy","Napoli, Campania, Italie":"Naples, Naples, Campania, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sanseverino","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Cono, Enrico, Rocco, Canio, Giuseppe, Vito.","Italian (mainly Naples): habitational name from San Severino Lucano in Potenza, San Severino Marche in Macerata, or Mercato San Severino in Salerno, all so named from the dedication of their churches to Saint Severinus (see   Severin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Severin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Christophe, Florien, Francois, Marcel, Monique, Olivier, Patrice.","German, Swedish, Italian (Veneto), Czech, Croatian, and Romanian; Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Severyn</b>); French (<b>Séverin</b>); Slovak (<b>Severín</b>): from a personal name, Latin <i>Severinus</i>, from the same root as <i>Severus</i> (see   Severe  ). This was borne by several early Christian saints, including bishops of Trier (2nd century), Cologne (4th century), and Bordeaux (5th century), and hermits of Paris (6th century) and Tivoli (8th century), as well as a 5th-century apostle of Austria.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): shortened form of <b>Severinovsky</b>, a habitational name for someone from Severinovka in Ukraine."]}]},{"name":"Guglielmo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guglielmo Sanseverino Signore di  Montesano was born about 1290, in Italy, his father, Barone Tommaso II Sanseverino, was 42 and his mother, Sveva d'Avezzano, Contessa di Tricarico Señora de Tricario, was 16. He married Margherita de Scocca in 1323. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1341, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1290–1341":"umbes 1290–1341","1290–1341":"1290–1341","1294–1361":"1294–1361","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1340–1393":"1340–1393","–1361":"–1361","–1377":"–1377","1250–1327":"1250–1327","1275–1308":"1275–1308","about 1290":"umbes 1290","10 May 1327":"10. mai 1327","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1250":"1250","1393":"1393","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1377":"1377","about 1288":"umbes 1288","1308":"1308","bet 1322 and 1325":"1323","Bassily, Hainaut, Belgium":"Bassilly, Hainaut, Belgia","Italy":"Itaalia","Napoli, Campania, Italy":"Napoli, Campania, Itaalia","Napoli, 